        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "src/toolkit/guards/tip-spend-cap.ts",
          "src/toolkit/guards/pay-spend-cap.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "tip-spend-cap.ts line 36: `if (amount > policy.maxPerTip)` checked before line 44: `if (!Number.isFinite(amount) || amount <= 0)`. NaN > 10 is false, so NaN would pass the first check and be caught by the second \u2014 but this depends on implicit NaN arithmetic.",
          "pay-spend-cap.ts line 34: `if (amount > policy.maxPerCall)` checked before line 42: `if (!Number.isFinite(amount) || amount <= 0)`. Same pattern.",
          "If the isFinite check is ever removed or moved, NaN amounts would pass the policy check silently"
        ],
        "suggestion": "Move the `isFinite(amount) && amount > 0` validation to be the FIRST check in both functions, before any policy comparison. This makes validation order self-documenting and removes the implicit NaN-comparison dependency.",
